<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>21091</anchor> <rss>typetopology.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Reference</taxon> <addr>typetopology</addr>  <route>typetopology.xml</route>  <authors><author><link href="martinescardo.xml" type="local">Martín Hötzel Escardó</link></author> </authors> <title>TypeTopology</title> <meta name="external">https://www.cs.bham.ac.uk/~mhe/TypeTopology/index.html</meta><meta name="bibtex">@misc{type-topology,
  title    = {{TypeTopology}},
  author   = {Escard\'{o}, Mart\'{i}n H. and {contributors}},
  url      = {https://github.com/martinescardo/TypeTopology},
  note     = {{Agda} development},
}</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Various new theorems in univalent mathematics written in Agda. By <link href="martinescardo.xml" type="local" title="Martín Hötzel Escardó">Martín Hötzel Escardó</link> and collaborators.</p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context/> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>21092</anchor> <rss>martinescardo.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Person</taxon> <addr>martinescardo</addr>  <route>martinescardo.xml</route>   <title>Martín Hötzel Escardó</title> <meta name="external">https://www.cs.bham.ac.uk/~mhe/</meta><meta name="orcid">0000-0002-4091-6334</meta><meta name="institution">University of Birmingham</meta><meta name="position">Professor</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter/> </tree></related> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>21093</anchor> <rss>2023-09-30.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Entry</taxon> <addr>2023-09-30</addr>  <route>2023-09-30.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>9</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>2023-09-30</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Today I finished my <link href="https://github.com/martinescardo/TypeTopology/pull/199" type="external">Agda formalization</link> in <link href="typetopology.xml" type="local" title="TypeTopology">TypeTopology</link> of the wild-categorical results that <link href="mikeshulman.xml" type="local" title="Mike Shulman">Mike Shulman</link> and I were hoping for in regard to <link href="jms-009S.xml" type="local" title="Strong impredicative encodings">strong impredicative encodings</link>. Then I translated these proofs into English. I started trying to re-deduce <link href="jms-004H.xml" type="local" title="Impredicative subuniverses are reflective">impredicative subuniverses are reflective</link> in this style, but noticed that there may be an issue: in the old proof, we split a very specific <link href="jms-003M.xml" type="local" title="Quasi-idempotent in a wild category">quasi-idempotent</link>, but here I am trying to split them all. I wrote to <link href="mikeshulman.xml" type="local" title="Mike Shulman">Mike Shulman</link> mentioning this to him.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>21094</anchor> <rss>2023-09-29.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Entry</taxon> <addr>2023-09-29</addr>  <route>2023-09-29.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>9</month> <day>29</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>2023-09-29</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p><link href="mikeshulman.xml" type="local" title="Mike Shulman">Mike Shulman</link> has sent me a potential proof of <link href="jms-003M.xml" type="local" title="Quasi-idempotent in a wild category">quasi-idempotence</link> for the generic element of a <link href="jms-003H.xml" type="local" title="Wild semicoherent natural transformations">semicoherent cone</link>, in our <link href="jms-009S.xml" type="local" title="Strong impredicative encodings">strong impredicative encodings</link> project. This relies on a “fattened” definition of semicoherence in the wild-categorical setting, similar to Mike’s <link href="jms-003W.xml" type="local" title="Semicoherence structure">fattened version</link> in the special case of subuniverses. <link href="mikeshulman.xml" type="local" title="Mike Shulman">Mike</link> points out that the condition, when specialized for cones over the identity functor, is much simpler than the general case. I am thinking that I might see if it is possible to formalize it in <link href="typetopology.xml" type="local" title="TypeTopology">TypeTopology</link>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></backlinks> <references/></backmatter></tree>